7. Create a correlation map of all the columns that contain numbers.

GPT-4o (Temperature = 0.2)

library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)

# Select numeric columns
numeric_columns <- df[, sapply(df, is.numeric)]

# Compute correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(numeric_columns, use = "complete.obs")

# Melt the correlation matrix for visualization
cor_melt <- melt(cor_matrix)

# Create the correlation map
ggplot(cor_melt, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Map", x = "", y = "", fill = "Correlation") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

10. Create a barplot of average mpg by class, colored by year. The years should be side by side.

GPT-4o (Temperature = 0.2)

library(ggplot2)

# Calculate average mpg (cty and hwy combined) by class and year
df$mpg <- (df$cty + df$hwy) / 2
average_mpg <- aggregate(mpg ~ class + year, data = df, FUN = mean)

# Create the barplot
ggplot(average_mpg, aes(x = class, y = mpg, fill = factor(year))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Average MPG by Class and Year", x = "Class", y = "Average MPG", fill = "Year") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

11. Calculate the correlation of cty vs hwy. Repeat that after log transformation. Collect these results and show them.

GPT-4o (Temperature = 0.2)

# Calculate correlation of cty vs hwy
cor_cty_hwy <- cor(df$cty, df$hwy, use = "complete.obs")

# Calculate correlation of log-transformed cty vs hwy
cor_log_cty_hwy <- cor(log(df$cty), log(df$hwy), use = "complete.obs")

# Collect and show results
results <- data.frame(
  Transformation = c("Original", "Log-Transformed"),
  Correlation = c(cor_cty_hwy, cor_log_cty_hwy)
)

results

## 1        Original   0.9559159
## 2 Log-Transformed   0.9556827

12. Hwy and cty represent miles per gallon (MPG) on the highway and in the city, respectively. Only keep cars more efficient than 15 MPG, but less than 40, on the highway. Add 0.5 to city MPG for correction. Perform log transformation on city MPG. Raise highway MPG to the second power. Calculate correlation coefficient of the two transformed variables.

GPT-4o (Temperature = 0.2)

# Filter cars with highway MPG between 15 and 40
df_filtered <- df[df$hwy > 15 & df$hwy < 40, ]

# Add 0.5 to city MPG for correction
df_filtered$cty <- df_filtered$cty + 0.5

# Perform log transformation on city MPG
df_filtered$log_cty <- log(df_filtered$cty)

# Raise highway MPG to the second power
df_filtered$hwy_squared <- df_filtered$hwy^2

# Calculate correlation coefficient of the two transformed variables
correlation <- cor(df_filtered$log_cty, df_filtered$hwy_squared, use = "complete.obs")

# Show the correlation coefficient
correlation
## [1] 0.9334202
